\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This report describes the first stage of a project to develop a Close-Kin
 Mark-Recapture (CKMR) model suitable for Pacific walrus (
\shape italic
Odobenus rosmarus divergens
\shape default
) samples from a non-lethal biopsy sampling program in the Chukchi Sea;
 lethal samples from hunters may be incorporated at a later date.
 Similar samples are also available from 2013–2017 cruises, and the current
 incarnation of the sampling program runs from 2023 thru 2027; it was originally
 envisaged as a genetic individual mark-recapture (IMR) project just for
 individuals, but the advent of CKMR raised the possibility of getting much
 more value-for-money by also using the samples for close-kin mark-recapture.
 Roughly, the gain is that each new sample not only "tags" a walrus for
 future recapture, but also its parents, its offspring (which may not yet
 be born), and its half-siblings.
 This multiplies the effective sample size considerably, and also gives
 somewhat different and complementary information about demographics compared
 to IMR.
 The only and very minor downside is that higher-quality genotyping is required
 for finding close-kin, but the additional cost is worth it, especially
 if it ultimately leads to reduced sample-size requirements.
 A further technical development, in about the same time frame as CKMR,
 has been the possibility of epigenetic ageing.
 Age data is immensely powerful for IMR as well as CKMR.
 The main novelty is to devise a computational framework for "ICKMR" that
 can handle both CKMR and IMR at once, including age information: this is
 new.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model we develop can be used while sampling is ongoing to anticipate
 what precision of various quantities-of-interest (such as adult abundance)
 is likely to be obtained by 2027 or before; to investigate the pros and
 cons of varying the way sampling is done; to design diagnostics that could
 be used to test for departures from baseline model assumptions (e.g., changing
 trends in abundance) and, of course, to fit the actual genetic data, once
 it arrives.
 We have also developed, independently, an individual-based simulation that
 can be used to test our estimation model.
 The work should result in a publication, as well as usable software; at
 this stage, we are producing a report and a preliminary version of the
 software, plus various results on likely precision and speculation on future
 options.
\end_layout

