\begin_layout Subsection
Biology and sampling from the viewpoint of CKMR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pacific walrus have a fairly typical "CKMR ideal mammal" life history, at
 least in terms of females: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
long-lived post-maturity;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
small litter size (at most 1 calf per "litter");
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
unlikely to re-mate with the same partner (thus few full sibling or full
 thiatic pairs; FSPs or FTPs);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
no obvious reason to expect some females to be much better breeders than
 others;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
highly mobile, so population is "well-mixed" from a sampling point-of-view
 (but see later), and with no genetic substructure expected;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
age estimates are expected for all samples; i.e., "DNAge" (epigenetic estimates)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Probably no need for calves, which are obvious.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of these are good news for the simplicity of CKMR modelling and the
 reliability of estimates.
 However, a CKMR model also has to take into account the details of how
 samples are obtained, and this does raise a few 
\emph on
potential
\emph default
 complications for walrus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
sampling is (mostly) non-lethal;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
male adults inaccessible, and likely to have substantial persistent individual
 variability in breeding success;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
"skippy" breeding cycle, with at most one calf every other year;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
incorporation of self-recaptures (IMR) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[ageing error from DNAge] (see below)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
[partial site fidelity to Russian or to American waters] (see below)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unavailability of male adult samples (at least in large enough numbers
 to be useful) basically means that we cannot model males at all, and so
 we simply do not include paternal half-sibling pairs (HSPs) in the model
 (even though there will be plenty in the dataset).
 The problem is that father-offspring pairs (FOPs) will not be available,
 and the demographics of paternal-half-sibling pairs (pHSPs) are determined
 not by overall adult male abundance and survival, but rather only by those
 males who persistently manage to breed.
 Substantial persistent heterogeneity in male breeding success is to be
 expected given the "lekking" behaviour of walrus, and there is no way just
 to distinguish from pHSPs alone between fewer male adults with lower variabilit
y, versus more adults with a small set of "supermales".
 Male adult survival estimates would be confounded by the rate at which
 hitherto-successful breeders "lose their mojo" and become invisible to
 the pHSP dataset.
 Further, male calves and juveniles are not useful in walrus IMR, because
 male juveniles undergo "permanent emigration" away from the summer sampling
 grounds, at whatever age they opt to stay south of the Bering Strait.
 Thus, like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Beatty2022walrusMR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we only try to model female dynamics.
 That said, it is perfectly reasonable to use male juveniles (and possibly
 calves; see Discussion) as potential 
\emph on
offspring
\emph default
 whose mothers might be recaptured.
 This gives an ICKMR models (or its POP component) access to a rather larger
 set of samples than IMR alone can use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the start of this project, we expected that the last two square-bracketed
 points would be important, and in fact developed the model equations and
 code with them in mind.
 However, as discussed below, we now do not expect either of them to matter
 much, so they have been switched off for design purposes.
 Those two phenomena account for a sizeable fraction of the model code.
 The spatial aspect in particular entails copious extra maths and has subtly
 unpleasant interactions with breeding-cycle mechanics; "unweaned" offspring
 may accompany their mother for several years whereas weaned ones go their
 own way, all of which requires modeling.
 It is with great relief that we have discarded those complications, at
 least for now! If the real data eventually suggest these need attention—
 which at present seems unlikely— they could (with appreciable effort) be
 switched on again.
 Alternatively, if they are definitively not important, the code could be
 simplified quite a lot, which is desirable long-term for clarity and ease
 of maintenance.
 For this report, we have used the full code but with zero age error and
 only one region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Epigenetic age ("DNAge")
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individual age data, or an informative surrogate (e.g., length for some fish)
 is essential for CKMR.
 If age "data" is sufficiently bad, it can make CKMR results almost uninterpreta
ble, even with large numbers of kin-pairs (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "bradford2018ckmr-gns"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an unfortunate example).
 All CK probabilities are basically conditioned on year-of-birth of a potential
 offspring or half-sibling, which is deduced from measured age and sampling
 date.
 Hence, if age is uncertain, then so is birth-year, and the probabilities
 need to be combined using weighted sums and awkward prior probabilities
 to make them conditional on 
\emph on
measured
\emph default
 age rather than true age.
 While generally possible, this is a lot of modeling work and does tend
 to reduce the overall information content of a CKMR dataset, leading to
 less-precise estimates than would result from precisely-aged datasets.
 In extreme cases such as that cited above, the reduction in information
 is drastic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Epigenetic age estimation offers a convenient way to get age estimates even
