\begin_layout Subsubsection
Spatial fidelity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summer, Pacific walrus use both the "eastern" (USA) and "western" (Russian)
 parts of the Chukchi and Beaufort Seas.
 For the foreseeable future, sampling will only occur in the former.
 This means that, in any given year, some animals will simply be unavailable
 for sampling.
 One concern about the project in general, has been whether such "spatial
 matters" will lead to bias.
 This has been a question for a number of CK projects, as well as for IMR,
 of course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that "spatial availability" only matters to CKMR/IMR
 if it is 
\emph on
persistent
\emph default
 and/or 
\emph on
heritable
\emph default
 at the individual level.
 In any IMR study, some animals will be unavailable, for whatever reason,
 during the initial marking phase, and some will be unavailable during the
 recapture phase.
 The key assumption required by IMR to avoid bias, is that those two availabilit
ies are 
\emph on
independent
\emph default
, conditional on whatever sample covariates are used in the model.
 If not, the analysis will be subject to the infamous curse of "unmodeled
 heterogeneity in capture probability", leading to bias.
 Sometimes appropriate conditioning covariates can be added to an IMR model
 to remedy that, sometimes not.
 But in any case, if availability is independent between occasions, there
 should be no bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on previous spatial CKMR planning exercises, we originally expected
 to implement a Hidden Markov Model (HMM) for Russian\SpecialChar breakableslash
American preference.
 Each adult's preference might change from year to year, but would likely
 be the same as last years; and an offspring would do whatever its mother
 did spatially until it "weaned".
 However, examination of satellite-tag data during the project contra-indicated
 such behaviour, at least as a commonplace phenomenon.
 Most animals in fact drifted between Russian and American waters 
\emph on
within
\emph default
 the course of a single season, so there seems no way they could exhibit
 a consistent preference 
\emph on
across
\emph default
 seasons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turned out that the spatial HMM entailed a lot of work (though it can
 be done, at least in principle); whether it could be fitted reliably just
 from CKMR/IMR data would depend on how extensive the early Russian sampling
 was.
 But since the satellite-tag data suggest it is probably not applicable,
 it seems best to put it aside for now, assume a simpler model applies where
 all (female) walrus are equally likely to get sampled (conditional on age)
 per year, and resurrect any persistent spatial model only if there is clear
 evidence down the track, e.g., from the CKMR data themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
General framework of CKMR and ICKMR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We follow the highly tractable approach to CKMR described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Bravington2016CKMR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The full likelihood of "who is related to who and how" is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
tractable, but we can reduce the data to a very large number of pairwise
 comparisons of genotypes, potentially between every sample and all other
 samples, in which each outcome is either "yes these two are a kin-pair
 of specified type (e.g., parent-offspring pair; POP)" or "no they are not".
 Comparisons are made separately for POPs, for HSPs (second-order kin),
 and for any other useful types of kin; the practical limit at present is
 that no kinship more remote than second-order can be reliably detected.
 The probability of each comparison yielding a "yes" depends both on demographic
 parameters, such as those related to abundance—the more "choices" an individual
 has for its mother, the lower the probability that any given female will
 turn out to be that mother—and also on the covariates of the individual
 samples, such as year of collection and age—an individual cannot possibly
 be the offspring of another individual that died before the first one was
 born.
 Each comparison is a Bernoulli (0/1) random event, and the overall log-likeliho
od is formed by adding up the log-likelihoods of every comparison, of which
 there can be literally billions in some projects (the number is proprotional
 to the square of the sample size).
 Crucially, for "large" populations (which certainly covers adult abundances
 of 100,000 and more), the great majority of samples will have no close-kin
 among the other samples, and all comparisons are effectively independent
 statistically, in that there is on average minimal statistical power to
 predict the outcome of the next comparison even based on knowing the outcomes
 of 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 others.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to incorporate IMR data into the same framework, treating
 a self-recapture as just another kin-type that can be tested for genetically:
 a "SP" (self-pair) rather than a POP, HSP, or FSP.
 All that is needed, is to develop the appropriate probability formulae.
 These are in some sense simpler than for CKMR itself but, as we shall see,
 there are some subtleties about how best to formulate the population dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The art of CKMR consists largely in devising probability formulae for the
 different kinships, appropriate to the biology and sampling process being
 considered, and conditional on covariates that can actually be measured
 for the two samples.
 It is usually easiest to start by working out the formulae for ideal measuremen
ts, i.e., if we knew everything we would like to about the two samples (age,
 sex, etc).
 Sometimes it is not possible to perfectly measure everything, e.g., if age
 data is imprecise
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A common example is for fish, where only length measurements may be available
 for some or all samples— although length is an important CKMR covariate
 in its own right for fish.
 But that is another story.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In such cases, the kinship probability formulae need to be "blurred", by
 summing probabilistically over the possible values that the true covariates
 might have been, given the imperfect measurements that were made of them.
 Happily, it seems as though that might not be necessary for walrus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the appropriately-blurred probabilities have been calculated for all
 possible categories (kinships, covariates) of comparison, the log-likelihood
 is readily calculated from the actual comparison outcomes.
 All comparisons with alike kinship-target and covariates can be grouped,
 to yield a single Binomial likelihood term, which can be very well approximated
 by a Poisson probability since the per-comparison chance of "success" is
