\begin_layout Standard
Sampling design is crucial for CKMR, because if too few samples are collected,
 or the samples are the wrong "type" (e.g., missing crucial age classes),
 or the covariates are not measured well enough, there will be too few useful
 kin-pairs to make any useful inference, notwithstanding a lot of effort
 and expense in collection, genotyping, etc.
 The quadratic relationship between sample size and expected kin-pairs (since
 the number of comparisons is quadratic in sample size) is often beneficial
 in CKMR— precision improvement per dollar spent increases as a sampling
 programme goes on— but has the flipside that too few samples means 
\emph on
far
\emph default
 too few kinpairs.
 Sadly, in our experience, CKMR projects are sometimes started as a rather
 ad hoc "experiment" on a shoestring budget with inadequate design; such
 projects do not usually end well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of walrus, there is already an effective IMR program in place,
 so the design process is not as critical as for most other species.
 Nevertheless, it is very useful to go through a design exercise because:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it enforces development of an appropriate CKMR model well before the real
 data and its complications arrive;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it gives realistic heads-up on what might be achieved from the study, important
 for longer-term planning;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it allows exploration of ways that the sampling program might be modified:
 would it yield better information for similar cost? etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of the independent-comparison Poisson-like-probability framework
 of CKMR, it turns out to be remarkably easy to predict precision of anything-of
-interest, 
\emph on
without
\emph default
 needing to do repeat simulations or even fit a CKMR model to simulated
 data.
 The basic point is that every comparison between two specific samples is
 practically statistically independent of the others, so as well as adding
 one term to the log-likelihood, it also adds one term (a matrix) to the
 second derivative
