 Once the expected Hessian is calculated, it can be inverted as usual to
 give the (expected) covariance matrix of the parameters, and from there
 standard errors can be calculated for any quantity-of-interest 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 (i.e., something that depends on the estimatable parameters) by applying
 the ubiquitous "delta method": 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{V}\left[f\left(\theta\right)|y\right]\approx f'\left(\hat{\theta}\left(y\right)\right)\mathbb{V}\left[\theta|y\right]f'\left(\hat{\theta}\left(y\right)\right)^{\top}$
\end_inset

.
