\begin_layout Standard
To show the single-comparison Hessian calculation in more detail, suppose
 we are considering a MOP comparison between potential-offspring 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and potential-parent 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, with covariates 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

 respectively (so one component of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{j}$
\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is female, otherwise the probability is of course 0).
 The demographic parameters are 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (a vector, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 below).
 Let the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{ij}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 denote the outcome, taking value 1 if 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 turns out to be 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's mother, and 0 if not; and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}\left(\theta\right)\triangleq\mathbb{P}\left[Y_{ij}=1|z_{i}z_{j}\theta\right]$
\end_inset

 be the probability of "success", to be calculated from some application-specifi
c formula as described in detail later on.
 Although 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is strictly speaking Bernoulli distributed, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 is so low (on the order of the reciprocal of population size) that a Poisson
 distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 is an excellent approximation.
 Omitting all subscripts etc where reasonably possible, the log-likelihood
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{\text{MOP}ij}$
\end_inset

 for the comparison is therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\Lambda=-p+Y\log p-\log Y!\label{eq:poi-app}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From standard statistical theory for Fisher Information, we know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{FI}\triangleq-\mathbb{E}_{Y}\left[\left.\frac{d^{2}\Lambda\left(Y;\theta\right)}{d\theta^{2}}\right\vert _{\theta_{0}}\right]=\mathbb{E}_{Y}\left[\left.\frac{d\Lambda\left(Y;\theta\right)}{d\theta}\frac{d\Lambda\left(Y;\theta\right)}{d\theta}^{\top}\right\vert _{\theta_{0}}\right]\label{eq:hess-jac-sqr}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

so it suffices to consider the first derivative of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poi-app"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda'_{k}\triangleq d\Lambda/d\theta_{k}$
\end_inset

 etc, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\Lambda'_{k}=-p_{k}'+\frac{Y}{p}p_{k}'=\frac{p'_{k}}{p}\left(Y-p\right)\nonumber \\
\implies\Lambda'_{k}\Lambda'_{\ell}=\frac{p'_{k}p'_{\ell}}{p^{2}}\left(Y-p\right)^{2}\nonumber \\
\implies\mathbb{E}\left[\Lambda'_{k}\Lambda'_{\ell}\right]=\frac{p'_{k}p'_{\ell}}{p^{2}}\mathbb{E}\left[\left(Y-p\right)^{2}\right]\nonumber \\
=\frac{p'_{k}p'_{\ell}}{p^{2}}\mathbb{V}\left[Y\right]=\frac{p'_{k}p'_{\ell}}{p}\label{eq:ELLT}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{V}\left[Y\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[Y\right]=p$
\end_inset

 for a Poisson distribution.
 A slight computational simplification comes from noting that, for any function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, we have by the chain rule that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\frac{d\sqrt{f\left(x\right)}}{dx}=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{f\left(x\right)}}f'\left(x\right)\label{eq:dsqrtf}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{E}\left[\Lambda'_{k}\Lambda'_{\ell}\right]=\frac{p'_{k}p'_{\ell}}{p}=4\left(\frac{p'_{k}}{2\sqrt{p}}\right)\left(\frac{p'_{\ell}}{2\sqrt{p}}\right)=4\frac{d\sqrt{p}}{d\theta_{k}}\frac{d\sqrt{p}}{d\theta_{\ell}}\label{eq:sqrt-trick}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

which avoids having to worry about 0/0 and streamlines some of the computation.
 The overall Fisher Information for the entire dataset is then formed by
 summing the per-comparison FI matrices.
 Note that all this theory is hinted at in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Bravington2016CKMR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and has been published piecemeal in various CKMR design projects.
 A more comprehensive paper has been in preparation since before Covid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 will involve several lines of code, and the only practical, reliable way
 to compute things like 
\begin_inset Formula $d\sqrt{p}/d\theta_{k}$
\end_inset

 is by Automatic Differentiation (for which the code needs to be written
 in TMB or some other special-purpose framework) or by numerical differentiation.
 The latter turns out to be perfectly adequate for design calculations,
 although for actually fitting to data (where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Lambda\left(y\right)/d\theta$
\end_inset

 itself is required for observed values 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, not the expected outer-product) Automatic Differentiation is much more
 reliable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The computational machinery to do these calculations is quite general-purpose,
 and has evolved during the last few years on several CKMR design projects.
 "All" that is needed is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CKMR model code that can calculate all the kinship probability arrays, given
 any set of parameter values;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a function that calculates a quantity-of-interest (for example, the abundance
 in a certain year; or the trend in abundance; or a survival rate; see section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
