\begin_layout Subsection
Parent-offspring pair (POP) probabilities
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:POP-probs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we are about to compare a potential-mother "Connie", sampled at
 age 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{c}$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{c}$
\end_inset

, to a potential-offspring "Jenny", sampled at age 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

, and therefore born in year 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}\triangleq y_{j}-a_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 We specifically restrict attention to comparisons that satisfy the following
 criteria:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Connie is female (though "Jenny" need not be); only female adult dynamics
 are being modelled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}=y_{c}$
\end_inset

 because there is some possibility that Jenny and her mother are still physicall
y associated, so within a single year their chances of being sampled are
 positively correlated;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}\geqslant1$
\end_inset

 because calves are not being used in the current model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}\geqslant2000$
\end_inset

 because we are only modelling population dynamics post 2000; thus the model
 has no idea how many adults were alive in any year before that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, we do not try to calculate probabilities for the excluded
 cases; we set the number of comparisons for such cases to zero; and we
 also set the number of MOPs for such cases to zero.
 (It is still worth checking those comparisons genetically just for interest's
 sake, but the results, positive or negative, are not used in the model.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With those restrictions in mind, we can distinguish two cases: 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{c}<b_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{c}\geqslant b_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In the former, Connie still has to survive several years in order to be
 Jenny's mother (note that Connie may be immature when sampled, but mature
 by the time of Jenny's birth).
 The MOP probability is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[K_{cj}=\text{MOP}|a_{c},y_{c},b_{j},\text{nonlethal}_{c}\right]=\nonumber \\
\frac{\text{Connie's Expected Reproductive Output in \ensuremath{b_{j}}|Connie alive and age \ensuremath{a_{c}} in \ensuremath{y_{c}}}}{\text{Total Reproductive Output (of females) in \ensuremath{b_{j}}}}\label{eq:MOP1}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can pick any unit-scale for ERO/TRO (units always cancel between the
 nominator and denominator in CKMR).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here it is convenient to choose "number of calves", so the TRO is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\beta_{2}}N\left(b_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\beta_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is the proportion of females with calves at any one time (section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Breeding-cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is a 
\emph on
very minor
\emph default
 approximation involved here; females start their breeding life in a non-pregnan
t state, and average fecundity over the first few years of adult life is
 
\emph on
slightly
\emph default
 below asymptotic fecundity.
 Thus the TRO "should" depend on the population's adult age composition.
 In practice, for walrus and many other mammals, the dominant reproductive
 output is from somewhat older animals (there are more of them) and the
 effect is negligible.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two components to Connie's ERO: first, she has to survive; second,
 she has to be calving in 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{ERO}_{c}\left(b_{j}|y_{c},a_{c}\right)=\Phi\left(y_{c}-b_{j}a_{c}\right)\times\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Br}\left(\text{age}=a_{c}+\left(b_{j}-y_{c}\right)\right)=2\right]\label{eq:MOP-RO}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Br}\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 is an individual's breeding state, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\left(\Delta t,a\right)\triangleq\text{survival probability for \ensuremath{\Delta t} years starting from age \ensuremath{a}}$
\end_inset

, obtained by multiplying together the right number of annual juvenile and
 adult survival probabilities.
 The term on the right involves Connie's age at 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 (assuming she survives).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience, define Fecundity via
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{fec}\left(a\right)\triangleq\frac{\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Br}\left(a\right)=2\right]}{\bar{\beta}_{2}},\label{eq:fec-def}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

so that immature animals have fecundity 0, and an average adult has fecundity
 1.
 (Fecundity at ages just after maturity may be slightly different.) Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[K_{cj}=\text{MOP}|a_{c},y_{c},b_{j},\text{nonlethal}_{c},y_{c}<b_{j}\right]=\nonumber \\
\frac{\Phi\left(y_{c}-b_{j},a_{c}\right)\times\text{fec}\left(a_{c}+\left(b_{j}-y_{c}\right)\right)}{N\left(b_{j}\right)}.\label{eq:MOP-future}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second case is if Connie is sampled after Jenny's birth.
 In that case, we know Connie was "alive" (or not born yet), so there is
 no survival term to worry about, but she may not have been mature.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{fec}\left(a\leqslant0\right)=0$
\end_inset

 (walruses cannot breed before birth) for convenience, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[K_{cj}=\text{MOP}|a_{c},y_{c},b_{j},\text{nonlethal}_{c},b_{j}<y_{c}\right]=\nonumber \\
\frac{\text{fec}\left(a_{c}-\left(y_{c}-b_{j}\right)\right)}{N\left(b_{j}\right)}.\label{eq:MOP-past}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Jenny's age at sampling does not appear (provided she is not a
