\begin_layout Subsection
Half-sibling pair (HSP) probabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we are now about to compare "Anna", born in year 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 (which can be calculated based on her age at sampling) to "Barry", born
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}$
\end_inset

, to check whether they have the same mother.
 This time, we impose the following criteria:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}>b_{1}$
\end_inset

 to avoid double-counting.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}\neq b_{2}$
\end_inset

 since litter-size is 1 and (presumably) Anna and Barry are not the same
 walrus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}\geqslant2000$
\end_inset

 since the population dynamics model does not stretch any further back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It helps to give a name to the mother of the first-born Anna, even though
 we will never sample that mother directly; let her be Mary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic idea is that Barry must have had 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 mother; what is the probability she was actually Mary, given what we know
 about Mary? The latter amounts to two things:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mary was alive, mature, and in "calving phase" at Anna's birth;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mary survived at least one more year after Anna's birth, otherwise Anna
 would not have lived long enough to be sampled (assuming she was sampled
 post-calfhood)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This second point is 
\size normal
\emph on
not
\emph default
 currently in the code, but will be added.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order for Mary to be Barry's mother, three things have to happen:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
she survives until Barry's birth;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
she is in the right breeding state then;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
she has to be the one lucky female amongst all the females that are in the
 right breeding state then.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The corresponding equation is arguably harder to follow than either the
 description above or the code below, because for compactness it becomes
 necessary to define a lot of extra symbols.
 Nevertheless, we shall proceed.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{B}}$
\end_inset

be the birth-years of Anna and Barry respectively; let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi\left(\Delta t\right)$
\end_inset

 be the probability that a female adult survives at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 more years from "now"; and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 be the breeding-cycle transition matrix, so that if the probability vector
 of an animal being in state (1,2,3) at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\left[t\right]}$
\end_inset

, then her probability vector at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\left[t+1\right]}=\Psi p^{\left[t\right]}$
\end_inset

.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\left[0\right]}=\left(0,1,0\right)^{\top}$
\end_inset

which is the probability vector of Mary's breeding state at Anna's birth
 (i.e., certain to be in calving phase), and recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\beta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the proportion of adult females in "calving phase", ie breeding state.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Anna and Barry are XmHSP}|b_{\text{A}}b_{\text{B}}\theta\right]\nonumber \\
=\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Anna's mum was also Barry's mum}|b_{\text{A}}b_{\text{B}}\theta\right]\nonumber \\
=\frac{\Phi\left(b_{\text{B}}-b_{\text{A}}-1\right)\times\left[\Psi^{b_{\text{B}}-b_{\text{A}}}p^{\left[0\right]}\right]_{2}}{N_{\text{ad}\female}\left(b_{\text{B}}\right)\times\bar{\beta}_{2}}\label{eq:xmhsp}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

where the subscript "2" means that we need the second element of the vector
 inside the square-brackets, i.e.
 the probability that Mary (given she was alive) was in calving phase at
 Barry's birth.
 (This could also have been written in a more POP-like way using probabilities-o
f-breeding state, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Br}\left(\text{Mary},b_{\text{B}}=2\right)|\text{Br}\left(\text{Mary},b_{\text{A}}\right)=1\right]$
\end_inset

, but with no particular benefit.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The walrus setting (or our assumptions about it) has actually made this
 probability rather simpler than it can be in other cases.
 In particular, all adult female walruses are assumed to have equal survival
 probabilities, regardless of age and breeding phase; and the breeding cycle
 is Markovian, so that once a walrus has reached calving-phase (like Mary
 at Anna's birth) her age does not affect her subsequent breeding phases
 nor her survival.
 In a "fish-like" situation, Mary's age (and size) at Anna's birth would
 also be important, because it affects both her subsequent future survival
 probabilities, and her fecundity if she reaches Barry's birthdate.
 Thus for "fish" it is necessary to sum across all the possible ages that
 Mary might have had, weighted by the probability that she was that age
 given that she was Anna's mother.
\end_layout

