\begin_layout Subsubsection
HSPs and skip-breeding
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:HSPs-and-skip-breeding"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This subsection is a mathematical treatment that does not apply directly
 to walrus, because we have already allowed for the female walrus' breeding
 cycle in our CKMR probabilities.
 Its purpose is to explain why failure to allow for semi-regular skip-breeding
 would otherwise lead to some bias in HSP-derived estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 (adult abundance, loosely defined).
 This is not obvious, so we provide a derivation that provides an indication
 of the size of bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of skip-breeding is that there is a regular 
\emph on
minimum
\emph default
 breeding interval.
 For simplicity, we just consider the case where breeding can only occur
 every 2nd (or, later on, every 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset


\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

) year.
 To "zeroth order", it might be expected that this makes no difference to
 the expected number of HSPs overall; although the mother of sample #1 only
 gets to breed every second year subsequently, whenever she does she only
 has to compete against half the females in the population, so the two effects
 cancel out.
 This is reasonable, but neglects the possibility of the mother dying in-between.
 Before equationizing all this, it is worth noting that skip-breeding has
 minimal effect on the estimation of 
\emph on
survival
\emph default
 from HSPs; the probability of finding an HSP-pair diminishes by a factor
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{k}$
\end_inset

 every 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 years whether there are skips or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the expected number of (maternal, say) later-born HSPs of any given
 sample Sally, based on one comparison per subsequent cohort.
 Each such comparison has probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 of having the same mother as Sally, 
\emph on
iff
\emph default
 that mother is still alive.
 For a species without skip-spawning (i.e.
 with a typical breeding interval of just 1 year), this expected number
 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is therefore given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
H_{1}\triangleq\frac{s}{N}+\frac{s^{2}}{N}+\frac{s^{3}}{N}+\cdots=\frac{N^{-1}s}{1-s}\label{eq:H1}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

because there is only probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 that the mother will survive from one year to the next.
 (Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is sometimes used instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 elsewhere in this document.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a similar situation in a species with a 2-year gap, the equation is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
H_{2}\triangleq0+\frac{s^{2}}{N/2}+0+\frac{s^{4}}{N/2}+...=\frac{2N^{-1}s^{2}}{1-s^{2}}\label{eq:H2}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

because there cannot be any maternal HSPs from odd-numbered later cohorts,
 but in the even-numbered later cohorts the mother (if alive) only has to
 compete against half the overall adults, since the remainder will be skipping
 that year.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\frac{H_{2}}{H_{1}}=\frac{2s}{1+s}\label{eq:Hrat21}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $s<1$
\end_inset

, the ratio is below 1— although not much below for a long-lived species
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\approx1$
\end_inset

.
 Misapplying a "no-skip" 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

-style model when there are "only" the number of HSPs from an 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}$
\end_inset

-situation, would lead to a positive bias in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}$
\end_inset

 (there are generally fewer HSPs from an 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}$
\end_inset

-situation than an 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

-situation for the same 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can generalize this to a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-year skip-breeding cycle:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
H_{k}\triangleq0+0+\cdots+\frac{s^{k}}{N/k}+\cdots+\frac{s^{2k}}{N/k}+\cdots=\frac{kN^{-1}s^{k}}{1-s^{k}}\nonumber \\
\implies\frac{H_{k}}{H_{1}}=\frac{ks^{k-1}\left(1-s\right)}{1-s^{k}}\label{eq:Hratk1}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For further algebraic insight, we can define the death rate 
\begin_inset Formula $d\triangleq1-s$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ll1$
\end_inset

 for a long-lived species, and expand in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\frac{H_{k}}{H_{1}}=\frac{k\left(1-d\right)^{k-1}d}{1-\left(1-d\right)^{k}}\nonumber \\
=\frac{k\left(1-\left(k-1\right)d+O\left(d^{2}\right)\right)d}{1-\left(1-kd+\tfrac{1}{2}k\left(k-1\right)d^{2}+O\left(d^{3}\right)\right)}\nonumber \\
=\frac{kd\left(1-\left(k-1\right)d+O\left(d^{2}\right)\right)}{kd\left(1-\tfrac{1}{2}(k-1)d+O\left(d^{2}\right)\right)}\nonumber \\
=\left(1-\left(k-1\right)d+O\left(d^{2}\right)\right)\left(1+\tfrac{1}{2}\left(k-1\right)d+O\left(d^{2}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
=1-\tfrac{1}{2}\left(k-1\right)d+O\left(d^{2}\right)\label{eq:Hratd}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, for given 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, the bias gets worse as 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 gets larger; but note that, across taxa, we would generally expect 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 to be negatively correlated since there is no point in having a long skip-breed
ing interval if you are unlikely to survive until the other end of it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some situations, it might reasonably be argued that bias of this magnitude
 is either unimportant, or reasonably accommodated by just using a "vanilla"
 (skip-free) HSP model with a pre- or post-calculated adjustment based on
 (anticipated, or estimated) survival rate and skip-breeding interval.
 In other words, the "vanilla" probability could be multiplied by a fixed
 factor 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 before use in the log-likelihood, in exactly the same way as the false-negative
 rate is accommodated.
 For walrus, with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\approx0.05$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 perhaps 3 or 4, perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0.9$
\end_inset

 would do a reasonable job.
 While not strictly valid statistically (because uncertainty in 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is ignored, and because 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 might in practice be "calculated" after-the-fact based on survival estimates,
 and then re-inserted in a second iteration of estimation), the offence
 would often be small.
 That said: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the actual bias will also depend on the temporal distribution of samples
 (the calculations above assume infinite future sampling, and a constant
 number of samples per year), so the "ideal" correction is not the same
 as the simplest one; and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
it is not usually 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 that difficult to devise a bespoke probability formula that properly accommodat
es biological nuances and avoids "all" bias, just as we have done here for
 walrus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\emph on
lethal-sample
\emph default
 POPs are hardly affected (unless there is correlation between breeding
 state and sampling probability, in which case a "vanilla" POP model might
 not work anyway).
 By the time the adult is lethally sampled, the offspring must already be
 born, so there is no "discounting" due to potential mortality.
 This would usually cover most POPs in the non-lethal case, too.
 With non-lethal samples, the effect on POP probabilities would depend whether
 sampling probability is linked to breeding-cycle status.
 For this report, we have generally assumed that it does not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Self-recapture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted previously, we only consider female samples for self-recapture,
 since juvenile males are prone to "permanent emigration" as well as true
 mortality, so do not yield readily-interpretable inferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Beatty2022walrusMR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 used a fairly complex IMR formulation to cope with historically-very-imprecise
 estimates of age (or, more realistically, of "stage") estimates.
 However, when accurate age data are available, the pairwise comparison
 probabilities for self-recapture are remarkably simple.
 Suppose two female samples are available with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2},a_{2}$
\end_inset

 in obvious notation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

 for definiteness.
 Then the probability that the first one (#1) is the same as the second
 is just
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[K_{12}=\text{SP}|y_{1}a_{1}y_{2}a_{2}\right]=\mathbf{I}\left(y_{2}-a_{2}=y_{1}-a_{1}\right)/N_{\female}\left(y_{1},a_{1}\right)\label{eq:SP}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The indicator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 is 1 if the two samples were born in the same year, or 0 if not; clearly,
 they can only be from the same animal if they were both born in the same
 year! If they were, then there is precisely one female alive at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 with age 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 who later became the second sample; and the chance that the first sample
 is that very female is the reciprocal of all such females, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\female}(y_{1},a_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 The implicit assumption here is simply that all females of the same age
 have the same survival and sampling probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation can also be formulated "the other way round", i.e., considering
 whether the second sample is the same as the first.
 The answer turns out the same, but the derivation is slightly different
 and 
\emph on
appears
\emph default
 to involve an explicit survival term.
 Specifically, we write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[K_{12}=\text{SP}|y_{1}a_{1}y_{2}a_{2}\right]\nonumber \\
=\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Sample 2 turns out to be the same animal as sample 1}|y_{1}a_{1}y_{2}a_{2}\right]\nonumber \\
=\frac{\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Sample 1 survived until Sample 2 was taken}\right]\times\mathbf{I}\left(y_{2}-a_{2}=y_{1}-a_{1}\right)}{N_{\female}\left(y_{2},a_{2}\right)}\nonumber \\
=\frac{\Phi\left(y_{2}-y_{1};a_{1}\right)\times\mathbf{I}\left(y_{2}-a_{2}=y_{1}-a_{1}\right)}{N_{\female}\left(y_{2},a_{2}\right)}\label{eq:other-way-round-self}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
