\begin_layout Standard
The big problem with applying eqn
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SP"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) in an ICKMR setting, i.e., with conditioning on age explicitly, is that
 it requires explicit calculation of all 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(y,a\right)$
\end_inset

 within the model.
 This is normally unnecessary with mammalesque CKMR, where the main information
 is 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 connected with aggregate adult abundance (via TRO).
 It is extremely convenient to work just with a "homogenous block" of adults,
 and there is in any case no direct information on population age composition
 unless extra data are used.
 One option is "just" to work with a fully-age-structured population dynamics
 framework— but that is a lot of work to develop (from experience in fisheries
 work) and requires modeling extra data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this project we have gone for a different option, which only uses "stage-stru
ctured" dynamics (adults and juveniles).
 This keeps the population dynamics simple, but to handle the IMR data,
 we do have to make extra assumptions about sampling selectivity.
 We assume that (
\shape italic
i
\shape default
) all (female) adults are equally likely to be sampled in a given year (i.e.,
 that probability does not depend on age, provided the animal is adult),
 and (
\shape italic
ii
\shape default
) that all juveniles age 1–6 are also equally likely— although juveniles
 overall may have different sampling probabilities to adults.
 That assumption may turn out to be unreasonable for juveniles especially;
 but it will only be possible to check once enough sample-age-composition
 data become available.
 However, if it does turn out to be the case that (say) 2yo are disproportionate
ly likely to be sampled (given their estimated abundance from the fitted
 model), then it would not be hard to adjust the stage-structured IMR equations
 to incorporate sample-composition-data and (estimated) selectivity.
 Sample sizes in this project are large enough that selectivity (i.e., the
 ratio of age-specific sample compositions to model-estimated pouplation
 age compositions) should be estimated with respectable precision and without
 "propagating" a lot of uncertainty into other parameter estimates.
 We therefore think that our current somewhat crude IMR sub-model should
 give a reasonable guide to ultimate precision, even if it gets adjusted
 somewhat in the cold light of real data.
 Note that similar assumptions appear to be made in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Beatty2022walrusMR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (to be confirmed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compute stage-structured self-recapture probabilities, we condition on
 the age of the first sample but 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 explicitly on the age of the second sample.
 However, we do condition on whether the second sample was juvenile (1–6)
 or adult (7+) at sampling, i.e., its "Devstage".
 If the age of the first, plus the intervening time between samples, would
 place the first sample in a different Devstage to the second sample, then
 the two cannot be the same animal.
 If the first sample would have reached the right Devstage, then we assume
 it is equally likely to be 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 of the females in that Devstage at that year (i.e., sampling is unselective
 within Devstage) and thus the chance it is the same as the second sample
 is the reciprocal of the Devstage abundance.
 The other consideration, of course, is that the first sample may not have
 survived the intervening years.
 This leads to the quite-simple code shown in Listing
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Self-prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The corresponding equation is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[\text{Sandy (sampled second) turns out to be the same animal as Freya (sampled first)}|a_{\text{F}}y_{\text{F}}d_{\text{S}}y_{\text{S}}\right]\nonumber \\
=\frac{\mathbf{I}\left[d\left(a_{\text{F}}+\left(y_{\text{S}}-y_{\text{F}}\right)\right)=d_{\text{S}}\right]\times\Phi\left(y_{\text{S}}-y_{\text{F}};a_{\text{F}}\right)}{N_{\female}\left(y_{\text{S}},d_{\text{S}}\right)}\label{eq:self-staged}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where: 
\begin_inset Formula $a/y/d_{\text{F/S}}$
\end_inset

 is the age, sampling year, or Devstage of Freya or Sandy as appropriate;
 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(a\right)$
\end_inset

 is the function that maps age to Devstage, with 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(a<7\right)=\text{"Juvenile"}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(a\geqslant7\right)=\text{"Adult"}$
\end_inset

; and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\female}\left(y,d\right)=\sum_{a}\mathbf{I}\left[d\left(a\right)=d\right]N_{\female}\left(y,a\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For devstage "Adult , the abundance is just 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\text{ad}\female}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 which is explicitly a variable in the population dynamics but, since the
