\begin_layout Standard
Although CKMR "magick" lets us avoid massive repeated simulations for the
 purposes of 
\emph on
evaluating
\emph default
 a proposed design, the best way to 
\emph on
check
\emph default
 the code of a complicated CKMR model is to see if it gives unbiased estimates
 against simulated data— which does require repeated simulations.
 However, the walrus CKMR R code is pretty slow (which does not matter for
 design-evaluation, since it only needs to be evaluated about 
\begin_inset Formula $2p$
\end_inset

 times where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the number of parameters) to the point that it could not practicably
 be used to fit lots of simulated datasets.
 But fitting turns out to be unnecessary, since we can approximate the outcome
 of fitting quite well with simpler and faster calculations.
 For each newly-drawn dataset 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{*}$
\end_inset

, we can readily evaluate the "Score vector", i.e.
 the derivatives of the log-likelihood at the true parameter values, written
 as
\begin_inset Formula $\left.d\Lambda\left(y^{*};\theta\right)/d\theta\right\vert _{\theta_{0}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda'\left(y^{*};\theta_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 These Scores should on average (across simulations) be close to 0 if the
 model and simulation agree.
 The definition of "close enough" can be determined relative to the Fisher
 Information 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{H}=-\mathbb{E}\left[\left.d^{2}\Lambda/d\theta^{2}\right\vert _{\theta_{0}}\right]$
\end_inset

, which is already being calculated for design use thanks to special properties
 of CKMR.
 We can use a similar idea to approximately find the MLE 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}\left(y^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

, just given the Fisher Information and the Score.
 Taking a Taylor expansion of the Score around the true parameter value
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, and putting the result the implicit equation that defines the MLE, which
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda'\left(y^{*};\hat{\theta}\left(y^{*}\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

 or just 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda'\left(\hat{\theta}\right)$
\end_inset

 for short, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\Lambda'\left(\hat{\theta}\right)=0\nonumber \\
\implies\Lambda'\left(\theta_{0}\right)+\Lambda''\left(\theta_{0}\right)\cdot\left(\hat{\theta}-\theta_{0}\right)\approx0\nonumber \\
\implies\hat{\theta}\approx\theta_{0}+\bar{H}^{-1}\cdot\Lambda'\left(\theta_{0}\right)\label{eq:approx-MLE}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is actually quite a good approximation to the full MLE, at least for
 reasonably informative datasets, since the observed and expected Fisher
 Information matrices tend to be close in practice.
 The point is that we can easily use eqn
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx-MLE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to examine the distribution of (approximate) MLEs across simulated datasets,
 without actually needing to fit the model and its rather slow R code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While simulating an entire CKMR dataset 
\emph on
de novo 
\emph default
is very slow (it is individual-based population dynamics over 50+ years),
 for model-testing it suffices to simulate 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 entire population history, then repeatedly sample entire datasets from
 that history— a much quicker process.
\end_layout

