\begin_layout Subsection
Utility of "nursing" status
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:nursy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It may be possible to obtain fairly-reliable information on whether each
 sampled females was nursing a calf or not (with "accompanied by an older
 juvenile" being a "not").
 This 
\emph on
might
\emph default
 have some value for CKMR estimates, since it informs on a female's state
 within the breeding cycle (state-2 or not-state-2), and thus has an influence
 on her MOP probabilities against animals born soon after or soon before
 her sampling-year; for example, a female cannot normally give birth in
 two successive years.
 We therefore also developed a MOP probability formula analogous to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MOP1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) that also condition on "nursingness" (i.e., with vs without calf), and explored
 what impact this extra conditioning data would have on overal precision.
 In brief, the answer is: minimal.
 The difference is practically undetectable for the abundance and survival
 parameters, although the breeding-cycle parameters are about 15% more precise
 using nursingness.
 From a modeling perspective, if nursing data was to be used at all, it
 would be much easier to build a separate log-likelihood component for "proporti
on observed nursing", but not to use individual measurements in conditioning.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the effect on precision is too small to make the modelling (and
 field) complications worthwhile, it is worth pointing out that a nursingness-co
nditioned MOP CKMR model is theoretically robust to any sampling-selectivity
 differences between nursing and non-nursing females.
 It might be easier, or harder, to sample the latter.
 The standard MOP formula (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MOP1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) implicitly assumes equal sampling probability, and so 
\emph on
might 
\emph default
be biased if that is not true.
 However, most MOP recaptures are well-separated in time, and after a couple
 of years the effects on current fecundity of being nursing-or-not a few
 years ago soon becomes unimportant.
 From a practical perspective, we therefore doubt there is much CKMR-related
 reason to include nursingness data at all (though it might be interesting
 in its own right, from a less narrow-minded perspective!).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have also thought about the potential value of recording "juvenile-accompanie
d" status for sampled (presumably adult) females.
 Our conclusion is that it would not be useful for CKMR, aside from the
 logistical challenges of getting reliable information during the hectic
 process of sampling.
 The original reason for thinking about it was in connection with spatial
 models, but those are are now "parked" until and unless ever needed.
 However, given the very limited gains anticipated from "nursing" data,
 it seems doubtful whether less-reliable "juvenile-accompanied" data would
 offer any worthwhile gain even in a spatial setting.
 See section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:juve-acco"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

