\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adjusting future sample composition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The precision of CKMR estimates can vary appreciably depending on the age
 composition of samples; for lethally-sampled fish, animals around the age
 of maturity tend to be less useful than younger or older ones, beccause
 they get fewer opportunities to "mark" offspring than the older ones, but
 are also less effectiing potential offspring because they were born longer
 ago.
 In general, the effects are not at all obvious.
 Depending on the species, it may sometimes be possible to tweak the sampling
 strategy, at least at the coarse level of targeting more juveniles or more
 adults.
