\begin_layout Subsection
Overall
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One caveat on these 
\emph on
estimated
\emph default
 precisions—impressive as they certainly are—is that they are closely tied
 to model correctness, and the quasi-steady-state model we have used is
 rather inflexible.
 With less-informative datasets, correctness or otherwise often does not
 matter; poetically speaking, the mountain of bias is usually submerged
 under a vast sea of uncertainty.
 However, as the quantity of data (recaptures) increases, the sea is drained
 and the mountain may become visible, or at least a shipping hazard.
 See section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:too-good"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
For the future, or not
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Qualitative design calculations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we have investigated 
\emph on
quantitative
\emph default
 precision under a "steady-as-she-goes" population dynamics model; abundance
 may be increasing or decreasing, but is assumed to be doing so steadily,
 and with the implied quasi-equilbrium age structure.
 Since nothing particularly drastic is thought to have happened to the Pacific
 walrus population since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\text{AD}2000$
\end_inset

, the model should deliver a usefully precise estimate of average abundance
 over that period, and at least place reasonable limits on any trend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality, of course, population dynamics do not remain completely stable
 for ever; the environment or the exploitation patterns may changes, an
 epidemic may burn through, and even if nothing else really changes, density-dep
endence is guaranteed to eventually kick-in unless the population is completely
 stable.
 A big motivation for monitoring is to be able to detect such changes— not
 necessarily via statistical yes/no hypothesis tests (hopefully not), but
 at least by noticing that observed and predicted values of some measurable
 quantity are diverging— or, if the modeling frame is sophisticated enough
 and the data powerful enough, by seeing that estimates of potentially-time-vary
ing parameters are moving.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current model does not include time-varying parameters.
 A foolhardy ingenue could keep using this model indefinitely as new data
 comes in;
\emph on
 
\emph default
it is true that, if the dynamics really do change (e.g., if carrying capacity
 halves), then the current model will 
\emph on
eventually
\emph default
 respond by changing estimated average abundance.
 In practice, that would happen through progressive shifts in the estimated
 RoI, and to a lesser extent in the reference-year abundance estimate.
 But this would still be a very coarse view of population dynamics; if the
 population was originally increasing over a 20-year period and has since
 decreased over the next 20 years, then it is not very useful to have the
 model say "things are stable"; that might arguably be a reasonable if coarse
 summary of the past 40 years, but would be a terrible guide for predictions.
 It would take a long time for new data to wash out the traces of the original
 dataset that was collected before the great population dynamics shift—
 possibly far longer than one would expect of a responsible monitoring program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One albeit-largely-theoretical advantage of line-transect-style surveys
 (i.e., where aggregate abundance is estimated 
\shape italic
de novo
\shape default
 every time) is that they respond quickly; if the true abundance halves
 because of an epidemic, the abundance 
\emph on
index
\emph default
 is likely to halve, too.
 In practice, this is a largely theoretical advantage, because the CVs on
 annual or regular surveys are usually so large that it takes a long time
 to accumulate strong-enough evidence— especially if changes are more subtle,
 as they usually are.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By contrast, CK and MR demographic monitoring (of abundance and other things)
 is intrinsically model-based
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In some situations one might be able to construct a series of "single-sample"
 Lincoln-Peterson-type MR estimates made independently, but that is usually
 not an efficient use of data, and makes little sense when there are "shared"
 demographic parameters such as survival rates.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and operates on an entire time-series at once.
 (The same is largely true of fish stock assessment, which often uses "independe
nt" annual abundance indices but only within the context of an overarching
 population dynamics model that incorporates all data at once.) Although
 we use a simple and rigid pouplation dynamics model in this report, the
 CKMR and IMR data do in principle provide enough information to fit very
 flexible population-dynamics models that respond quite quickly to changes
 (e.g.
 decreased calf production).
 However, it is a rather subtle question as to 
\emph on
when
\emph default
 abundance is "really" being estimated, and thus how quickly a CKMR monitoring
 program can expect to respond to changes.
 The next section gives some mathematical\SpecialChar breakableslash
theoretical perspective, followed
 by a slightly more practical take on the implications for walrus monitoring
 in section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:detecting-changes"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
How up-to-date are CKMR and IMR estimates?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:utd"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pairwise kinship probabilities are always determined by what was happening
 at the birth of of (one or both) members; at that time, there is always
 an element of "competition" between one animal and all others for the "honour"
 of parenthood.
 However, it is not obvious what this means for the responsiveness of CKMR
 or ICKMR models to changes in abundance; are the empirical data "really"
 telling us about abundance in the distant past, or the near past, or the
 present? To explore this further, consider for simplicity a population
 under lethal sampling where adult females can breed every year and are
 reproductively homogenous, with abundance 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{y}$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The MOP probability for a potential-offspring born in year 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, compared to a potential-parent sampled after 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and of sufficient age to have been mature at 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, is just
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[\text{MOP}|b,\cdots\right]=\frac{1}{N_{b}}\label{eq:simplest-MOP-utd}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the information is all back-dated to the birth of the potential-offspring.
 Even without an explicit population dynamics model (e.g.
 in extremis allowing the 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{y}$
\end_inset

's to be free parameters), given enough data we could eventually reconstruct
 abundance for any past year where a sample was born; however, there will
 not be many suitable comparisons for the most recent years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The situation is different for HSPs.
 For two samples born in 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{2}$
\end_inset

(with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}<b_{2}$
\end_inset

 for definiteness), the probability that they turn out to share a mother
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mathbb{P}\left[\text{XmHSP}|b_{1}b_{2}\cdots\right]=\frac{\phi^{b_{2}-b_{1}}}{N_{b_{2}}}\label{eq:simplest-HSP-utd}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the adult survival probability (here assumed constant in age and time
 for simplicity).
 This is simply the probability that #1's mother survives the intervening
 years, divided by the competition she will then experience to be #2's mother
 as well.
 The denominator pertains to the birth of the 
\emph on
later-
\emph default
born sample #2.
 The presence of 
