\begin_layout Subsection
Grandparent-Grandchild Pairs (GGPs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
HSPs are genetically indistinguishable from GGPs.
 This creates a difficulty in some CKMR applications, because demographically
 HSPs and GGPs are both "common" when considered over long-enough timescales,
 but they have very different probabilities conditional on individual covariates.
 Thus, interpreting actual GGPs as if they were HSPs would lead to biased
 parameter estimates: not just because the number of kin-pairs would be
 artificially inflated, but more seriously because e.g., the birth-gap between
 GGPs is typically much longer than between HSPs, so that survival estimates
 (based on declining HSP frequency as birth-gap increases) would be distorted.
 However, the problem sometimes carries the seeds of its own resolution.
 Birth-dates of a GGP must be separated by at least twice the age-of-maturity,
 and usually by rather more than that; thus, by constraining the comparisons
 which get included in the model to those which are 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
 unlikely to include GGPs based on birth gap, unbiased estimates can be
 achieved usually with little cost in reduced sample size (we are not making
 use of any HSPs that are separated by a long gap, but there won't be many
 of those anyway).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That approach is the simplest, and the one we have followed here, taking
 a 16-year maximum gap as pretty safe GGP-wise.
 It works well for species with high-ish age-at-maturity, and when there
 is not much uncertainty about individual age (which we expect for walrus).
 The alternative, more complicated, approach is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
specifically develop CKMR probability formulae for GGPs as well as for HSPs,
 conditional on the same covariates;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
add
\emph default
 the two probabilities, at each covariate combination, to get the probabiliity
 that "this pair will genetically look like an HSP or GGP" (valid since
 those kinships are mutually exclusive).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle, this is statistically optimal because it avoids having to
 discard any comparisons.
 And step 1 is not really any 
\emph on
more
\emph default
 difficult than any other aspect of CKMR.
 However, it does all entail substantial extra work, especially when there
 is a non-annual breeding cycle.
 Since relatively few potential comparisons are going to cover a birth-gap
 of >16 years while still having the first birth post-2000, we feel that
 truncate-and-ignore is a justifiable treatment for walrus GGPs, at least
 during design.
 When the real data arrives, the model could perhaps be expanded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that FTPs ("Full-Thiatic Pairs" e.g., uncle-niece) are also genetically
 indistinguishable from HSPs and GGPs.
 However, they are rare in long-lived species that do not tend to repeat-mate
 with the same partner, because an FTP already implies the existence of
 a FSP in the previous generation, and FSPs require a repeat-mating.
 In a species like walrus, the great majority of sibs are half- rather than
 full-sibs.
\end_layout

