\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Age composition data are crucial to most fish stock assessments, whether
 obtained directly from e.g., otolith readings, or indirectly and implicitly
 via length composition data.
 Mostly, such data come from catches, and are therefore likely to be subject
 to selectivity biases (i.e., not to be representative of the population's
 composition); a lot of fisheries modeling effort goes into dealing with
 selectivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Individual
\emph default
 age data, or some surrogate, are basically essential for CKMR, because
 they are used in conditioning the probability formulas.
 However, age 
\emph on
composition
\emph default
 data (regardless of kinship) are not essential, at least not for classically
 mammalesque species— i.e., where all adults are basically the same in "samplabili
ty" and fecundity, or at least where there is not likely to be much systematic
 age effect on those parameters.
 Nevertheless, age composition data are potentially informative about detailed
 population dynamics, especially if the composition starts changing over
 time.
 It then becomes possible to infer changes in, say, breeding rates or age-specif
ic survival rates, thus decomposing the catch-all "RoI" into its drivers,
 and improving predictive (and reactive) power.
 Selectivity still needs to be grappled with, since e.g., juveniles and adults
 are likely to have different per capita sampling probabilities, and that
 weakens the effective information content to some extent.
 In general, models using explicit age composition data require a lot more
 parameters.
 A full age-structured population dynamics model for walrus would entail
 modeling decisions (and parameters) to deal with the "initial" population
 age composition (in 2000, say).
 On the other hand, once the rather formidable age-structured machinery
 has been set up, there may be fewer awkward decisions to take in other
 aspects, e.g., about approximating the information from self-recaptures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main benefit of age compositions for mammalesque CKMR modeling (particularly
 for medium-term predictions) would probably be for juveniles, although
 it is in this part of life that selectivity is most annoying (i.e., strongest
 links to age).
 The population age composition of 
\emph on
adults
\emph default
 is not particularly useful for mammalesque CKMR, at least in "bottom line"
 terms of estimating absolute abundance and recent trend, although it can
 be informative about long-term.
 In this study, we chose to ignore the future availability of age composition
 data, in favour of simplifying the modeling to "stage-structured dynamics",
 with a lot fewer parameters to estimate— although the need to handle self-recap
ture data (which does not feature in other CKMR designs that we have seen)
 undoes some of that simplification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see two main options for CKMR-driven walrus models:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
block-structured, no use of age 
\emph on
composition
\emph default
 data, some fudging of individual MR data, few parameters, mostly simpler
 code;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
