\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The code for this project embodies a full-featured ICKMR model that could
 likely be applied with few or no modifications to real walrus data—provided
 that DNAge error indeed proves to be ignorable for this species.
 The precision of estimated parameters (for females) should be very good
 by 2027, and possibly before that given the past sample sizes.
 There is the opportunity to explore tweaks to the sampling scheme, but
 the existing scheme seems likely to be so effective that there may not
 be much point.
 When enough real data arrive, it 
\emph on
might
\emph default
 be worth considering a move to an explicitly age-structured model that
 also uses calf samples directly, and that includes calf survival as an
 explicit parameter.
 At that same time, it 
\emph on
might
\emph default
 also be worth considering models with time-varying parameters, since the
 period being modelled is quite long (nearly 30 years), the world does not
 stand still, and—crucially—for once the dataset should be powerful enough
 to allow it.
 However, the existing model may be adequate as is; it all depends on the
 management purpose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CKMR is new enough that most species seem to bring their own wrinkles, and
 walrus have indeed turned out quite wrinkly.
 The complications of noisy age estimates and spatial fidelity, which we
 expected to be major issues when this project began, now seem less likely,
 and probably ignorable at least until the data arrive to check them.
 However, the addition of self-recapture data (IMR)— which looks simple
 in principle for ICKMR— has turned out more complicated than we anticipated,
 because the very simple population dynamics model that usually works well
 for mammalesque CKMR does not fit IMR equally well.
 Nevertheless, we do now have a reasonable joint ICKMR model, and it is
 interesting to see how much additional inferential power is brought by
 the CKMR data— data which is effectively "free", in terms of marginal cost
 on top of existing sampling.
 The answer is: a lot.
 Depending on what one is trying to estimate, precision is two to three
 times higher with CKMR data than without it.
 For walrus, CKMR is worth the effort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This design project has, by intention, the comparative "luxury" of being
 able to test the estimation code against an individual-based simulation
 framework that was written completely separately.
 Although both modellers are trying to embody the same biology and sampling,
 there was no collusion about the code for the two parts, and indeed the
 programs for individual-forward-simulation and for aggregate-backward-estimatio
n in CKMR look 
\emph on
completely
\emph default
 different.
 This is a very valuable exercise.
 At the time of writing (after only the very first attempt at testing),
 there is a fairly small but significant difference between the two, which
 still has to be sorted out.
 There are several places on either side where minor bugs or "discrepancies
 of interpretation" might have crept in.
 At any rate, the differences are fairly small in the scheme of things,
 and we do not think they substantially weaken our general conclusions about
 expected precision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of code, the existing model should to be fully translated into
 TMB before application to real data (though in fact the walrus model is
 simple enough that an R-only version might work— for many species, that
 is not the case).
 In fact, we have already translated an early version of the R code, but
 it will need revision.
 Since this project began, there have been some improvements in the TMB
 toolkit which should make the process less gruesome; the substantive parts
 of the code can be made to look very similar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several ways the existing model might be improved.
 One is to consider the use of calf samples (which we have ignored to date);
 that will entail consideration of how they affect precision, and to what
 extent they are a useful the quantitative value.
 Another is to incorporate lethal samples from hunts.
 For the longer-term, it is possible that extensive hunt samples might contribut
e enough precision to allow a less-intense direct-sampling program, while
 still maintainineg adequate precision for management.
\end_layout

